abor, and the formation of an information-intensive New Economy. By examining his own evolving interpretations of Los Angeles and the debates on the so-called Los Angeles School of urban studies, Soja argues that a radical shift is taking place in the nature of the urbanization process, from the familiar metropolitan model to regional urbanization. By looking at such concepts as new regionalism, the spatial turn, the end of the metropolis era, the urbanization of suburbia, the global spread of industrial urbanism, and the transformative urban-industrialization of China, Soja offers a unique and remarkable perspective on critical urban and regional studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aCity planningzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aRegional planningxCaliforniaxLos AngelesxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aRegional planningzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aSociology, UrbanxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aSociology, UrbanzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095763340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520957633/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles